00:12:24.799 --> 00:12:26.799
So, who am I?

00:12:26.799 --> 00:12:28.799
This is me.

00:12:28.799 --> 00:12:33.799
And I actually recently graduated with my master's degree.

00:12:33.799 --> 00:12:39.799
I did the whole, like, full-time work and full-time school thing while I was doing my master's degree.

00:12:39.799 --> 00:12:48.799
As I was working at Posit, you know, I was writing this Vetiver framework and finishing my degree.

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:58.799
And part of what kind of made me so excited about MLOps was because of what I had learned in my degree.

00:12:58.799 --> 00:13:06.799
And when I was learning about data science, my degree was in data science, sort of, like, half computer science, half data science.

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:09.799
Kind of one of those weird in-between things.

00:13:09.799 --> 00:13:13.799
But I learned about a data science workflow that looked kind of like this.

00:13:13.799 --> 00:13:15.799
You know, you start with some data.

00:13:15.799 --> 00:13:21.799
You collect it, whether that's from an API or from, like, CSVs or people are just handing you data.

00:13:21.799 --> 00:13:23.799
You know, you get this data.

00:13:23.799 --> 00:13:28.799
And then you get to use some tools to understand the data.

00:13:28.799 --> 00:13:32.799
And that's things like the tidyverse or data table.

00:13:32.799 --> 00:13:36.799
If you are in the R world, I actually work in the Python space as well.

00:13:36.799 --> 00:13:39.799
So, you're going to see some Python references.

00:13:40.799 --> 00:13:44.799
So, I might use something like Pandas or NumPy or Suba.

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:54.799
If you guys are looking ever for a dplyr-like Python package, Suba is amazing.

00:13:54.799 --> 00:13:56.799
And so, you have this data.

00:13:56.799 --> 00:13:57.799
You've cleaned it.

00:13:57.799 --> 00:13:58.799
You've understood it.

00:13:58.799 --> 00:14:04.799
And then in this data science workflow, you train and evaluate some sort of model.

00:14:04.799 --> 00:14:13.799
That's using things like Carrot or tidymodels and R or Keras or scikit-learn or PyTorch and Python.

00:14:13.799 --> 00:14:16.799
Some of those are in both languages.

00:14:16.799 --> 00:14:24.799
And as I was learning, you know, all of these different data science things, I was learning about best practices in data science.

00:14:24.799 --> 00:14:26.799
And I will give you guys a warning.

00:14:26.799 --> 00:14:29.799
There is Python code on my slides.

00:14:29.799 --> 00:14:32.799
This is not to scare anyone off.

00:14:32.799 --> 00:14:37.799
I personally am a Python person primarily.

00:14:37.799 --> 00:14:39.799
The end will be in R.

00:14:39.799 --> 00:14:43.799
But I just want to show you guys that, like, these concepts are the same in both languages.

00:14:43.799 --> 00:14:47.799
And these frameworks actually exist in both languages.

00:14:47.799 --> 00:14:50.799
So, you're going to get a dose of both.

00:14:50.799 --> 00:14:57.799
So, some best practices in data science are things like setting your seed for reproducibility.

00:14:57.799 --> 00:15:06.799
If you've worked in different data science worlds, this is kind of the first thing you learn to do to make sure, you know, when you load data, it's always the same.

00:15:06.799 --> 00:15:10.799
Just good things for this reproducible data science workflow.

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:19.799
And you also learn about best practices like splitting your data into test and training data sets.

00:15:19.799 --> 00:15:24.799
So, you're not, you know, giving your model the answers while you're training it.

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:32.799
You know, there's whole workbooks, whole textbooks on these best practices that we will not dive into today.

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:36.799
But it's good to know, like, these are very well-known things.

00:15:36.799 --> 00:15:40.799
You know, making sure you're choosing the right feature engineering for your model.

00:15:40.799 --> 00:15:45.799
Making sure you're putting these things into a pipeline if it's feature engineering that you're training.

00:15:45.799 --> 00:15:53.799
These are things that span across languages that you kind of always have to keep in mind as you are doing data science.

00:15:53.799 --> 00:16:04.799
But my first job as a data scientist before I was building software, the problems I encountered as a data scientist were different.

00:16:04.799 --> 00:16:13.799
I knew all of these best practices, but I realized, you know, the issues I was running into is how do you share data with your teammates?

00:16:13.799 --> 00:16:18.799
Like, are you emailing everybody CSVs or Excel files?

00:16:18.799 --> 00:16:22.799
You know, how are you sharing models with each other?

00:16:22.799 --> 00:16:27.799
Is it on Git? Is it, again, emailing things around?

00:16:27.799 --> 00:16:36.799
And how do you get people who don't code as much to be able to engage with the things that you have created?

00:16:36.799 --> 00:16:43.799
You know, oftentimes this is, you know, at the end you have a shiny application that, you know, your model is running in.

00:16:43.799 --> 00:16:46.799
And how do you put that model into a shiny application?

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:57.799
There's a lot of different problems when you're putting this whole cycle of data science together that are just kind of beyond the best practices that I had learned in school.

00:16:57.799 --> 00:17:00.799
So I learned that these practices maybe weren't enough.

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:06.800
And I also learned that if you develop models, you can operationalize them.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:13.800
And so this is making sure that your models are in some sort of larger ecosystem.

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:18.800
Maybe that's on Git. Maybe that's shared with your teammates in some way.

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:23.800
Making sure that the model isn't just on your computer.

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:28.800
So I learned that, you know, you want to bring your model outside your computer.

00:17:28.800 --> 00:17:33.800
And you want to learn kind of the best practices of how to do that as well.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:41.800
And so those best practices for machine learning operations to operationalize your model are called MLOps.

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:46.800
And so there's a lot of hype around this word that I find online.

00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:48.800
It's like, I don't even know what MLOps is.

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:55.800
You can read all of these different, like, startups and you read their documentation and you don't really know what they're doing at the end of it.

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:57.800
It's kind of stressful to get started.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:17:59.800
But here is a kind of one-liner.

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:07.800
MLOps is a set of practices to deploy and maintain machine learning models in production reliably and efficiently.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:19.800
So where we had those best practices like setting a seed or splitting your training and testing data to build a model, MLOps are the same different set of practices.

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:32.800
But, you know, it's a set of practices to make sure that the model, when it leaves your computer, can still be reproducible and shared in a safe way with others.

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:50.800
In my first job, when I was starting to learn about MLOps and learn how to deploy models, I was struggling because there was a set of tools that were really based on Kubernetes.

00:18:50.800 --> 00:19:02.800
And it felt like I almost had to be like a cloud expert and then also like a DevOps expert and like maybe kind of a systems architect and also a data scientist.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.800
And that felt like way too much.

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:07.800
These practices are hard.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:13.800
It gets models off your computer into some sort of larger system.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:20.800
And sometimes tools don't necessarily feel ergonomic for data scientists.

00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:29.800
It felt like these tools were not really made for people with a skill set that I had coming from a purely data science background.

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:33.800
And that is kind of how Fediver was created.

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:47.800
I ended up changing career paths from doing data science to building data science tools and making these MLOps tools to feel like an extension of what people are already doing.

00:19:47.800 --> 00:19:52.800
So I do work for Posit, the company that was formerly known as RStudio.

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:57.800
Fediver is funded by Posit because I'm an developer for them.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:06.800
So it's no surprise that while I'm showing you Python code and while I primarily write in Python, there is also an R version of Fediver as well.

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:20.800
The code actually looks almost identical, and that was on purpose, especially realizing that people sometimes might have to work in different languages or collaborate with people who are using different languages.

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:30.800
We wanted to make tools that feel super easy to go back and forth so it doesn't feel like you have to start from zero if you're moving between languages.

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:40.800
So part of the idea of Fediver is that there's this life cycle where you collect and understand and evaluate your model.

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:56.800
But it wants to fill in the gap of how to get this model out into the real world, making predictions from real world data in a really safe, reproducible way.

00:20:56.800 --> 00:21:09.800
So some of the tasks that Fediver helps with, actually I'm going to go back to this because I like this slide better, is to version your models, to deploy your models, and to monitor your models.

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:12.800
And those are the three main tasks Fediver focuses on.

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:32.800
There are many, many other best practices that ML Ops encases, but we really wanted to narrow down what, when I say we, it's me and the Fediver team, wanted to narrow down what we thought was important for people who are just starting to deploy models,

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:36.800
who are just trying to figure out what this world is and what it means for them.

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:40.800
So the first step of this is versioning.

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:58.800
And when people think of versioning, it's normally in the context of Git, where you have some sort of central repository of files that people can read and write to, like push and pull to, but people actually version a lot of things.

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:03.800
And they normally version things pretty badly, actually.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:17.800
I think of kind of how I am building models, kind of my past, and I would version, you know, I would start with a model and I save it probably as a RDS file or as a Joblib file.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:21.800
So I save my model, I name it model, or maybe something a little better.

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:29.800
And then maybe you update some of your features and you get new data, and then you re-save it and it's model final.

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:38.800
And then maybe you realize that it needs a little bit more tweaking, and so you have your model, final, final, and you guys see where this goes.

00:22:38.800 --> 00:22:54.800
You end up with all of these versions of one object that maybe you need information from multiple files of these, but it's not really scalable and these aren't really reproducible.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:23:00.800
And it doesn't really make much sense because then you have to remember which is which and all of this other information.

00:23:00.800 --> 00:23:06.800
Versioning really is the foundation for success in machine learning deployments.

00:23:07.800 --> 00:23:13.800
And also maybe not just for machine learning deployments, but a lot of reproducibility problems.

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:21.800
A well-versioned system, a well-versioned file is normally going to be easier to share.

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:26.800
It's going to be easier for you to share with yourself six months from now as well.

00:23:27.800 --> 00:23:38.800
So when we think about our ideal versioning system, it would be nice if all of these files lived in a central location, so you don't have to search between different directories.

00:23:38.800 --> 00:23:49.800
Maybe if they were discoverable by a team, so something that's not just on your computer, but something that can be hosted in a cloud environment between people.

00:23:50.800 --> 00:24:11.800
And it's also really nice if things can be loaded right into memory, so you don't have to, like, the problem I have with Git sometimes with data is you'll have to go download the data if you can't in an easy way, load it onto your local computer, open up RStudio, load the data in that.

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:14.800
So it's a few extra steps.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:25.800
And sometimes Git is difficult for people who don't have that skill set, or maybe that's not their primary job is to be working in these version control systems.

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:31.800
So something that helps Benefer out is actually another package called Pins.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:35.800
And we're going to do, like, a very small Pins side quest.

00:24:35.800 --> 00:24:44.800
You don't actually have to install Pins to use Benefer, but they play together really nicely, and they're kind of built alongside each other.

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:46.800
And Pins is...

00:24:50.800 --> 00:24:51.800
I'm missing a slide, but that's okay.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:25:03.800
So Pins is a package that publishes data, models, other R objects, and it makes it easy to share them between projects and with your colleagues.

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:17.800
Some things that might be considered good uses for Pins are, like, an ETL pipeline that will store a model or summarize data sets maybe once a day.

00:25:18.800 --> 00:25:24.800
Pins, though, is not meant for multiple writing things back and forth.

