00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:37.800
So it can be pinned in a variety of locations.

00:26:37.800 --> 00:26:42.800
Pins, we can pin models, but we can also pin other things, like data.

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:51.800
So if you have things as a CSV or as something in, like, an arrow format, you can pin actual full files.

00:26:51.800 --> 00:26:56.800
I know people who pin a lot of things, but I don't know if you guys have ever done this.

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:00.800
You can pin actual full files.

00:27:00.800 --> 00:27:10.800
I know people who pin entire packages, actually, and anything that's an RDS object, you are able to pin.

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:22.800
So what's actually super useful about pins, this is kind of a side quest, is that it actually is meant to go across languages as well.

00:27:22.800 --> 00:27:29.800
So if you are pinning something that can be loaded in R and Python, I collaborate with my teammates all the time.

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:46.800
I'll pin up data in R because it's a lot easier to clean data in R, and then I'll read it into Python and use that exact same data set that I have just updated in R, pull it into Python for machine learning, or something like that.

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:52.800
So it's good for pipelines where things is read and are updated.

00:27:52.800 --> 00:28:00.800
Pins is not really meant to have multiple people writing data to it at once.

00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:06.800
You can have as many people as you want reading from it, but you can't have multiple writes.

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:08.800
That is kind of a downside of pins.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:16.800
One thing that we see people try to do, and that I just kind of want to get ahead of, is don't try to make a Google form with a pin.

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:19.800
These are just files.

00:28:19.800 --> 00:28:24.800
So if you're trying to have multiple people update the same file at once, it might get corrupt.

00:28:25.800 --> 00:28:37.800
But if one person or, say, some sort of system is reading and writing this pin one at a time, or you want to share something for multiple people to ingest, pins is good.

00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:39.800
Please don't make a Google format of it.

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:44.800
I can tell you right now, I've had some horror stories from that.

00:28:45.800 --> 00:28:51.800
But what works really well is people will have GitHub actions running where it will update a notebook or something like that.

00:28:51.800 --> 00:28:55.800
And pins is kind of a perfect solution for them.

00:28:55.800 --> 00:28:58.800
And pins is built to be super easy to use.

00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:03.800
This is what it looks like in Python in R.

00:29:03.800 --> 00:29:10.800
It's essentially just model board equals board temp.

00:29:11.800 --> 00:29:18.800
So this is what you would do if you wanted to make a board that goes directly on your computer.

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:24.800
Pins works off this mental model where, imagine you create kind of like a pin board.

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:30.800
I kind of have one right here on my wall, where it's a collecting spot for a lot of different information.

00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:34.800
So you make a board and you pin different objects to it.

00:29:35.800 --> 00:29:43.800
For this, it will be something that doesn't last on my computer, but it's good for demo purposes or if you're just trying stuff out.

00:29:43.800 --> 00:29:46.800
This is a Python specific thing I won't dig into.

00:29:46.800 --> 00:29:51.800
If you're interested in what a pickle file is in Python, I'm happy to discuss.

00:29:51.800 --> 00:29:57.800
So this is the temporary board.

00:29:57.800 --> 00:30:06.800
If you want to change it to be a S3 board, it would just be board underscore S3 or board underscore Azure or whatever.

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:11.800
So it's super easy to switch between boards or something like that.

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:14.800
And this is where Vediver comes in.

00:30:14.800 --> 00:30:18.800
So let's say we are in our data science workflow.

00:30:18.800 --> 00:30:21.800
We have created our model.

00:30:21.800 --> 00:30:23.800
It's called RF pipe.

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:27.800
This is like a random forest pipeline that I created.

00:30:27.800 --> 00:30:29.800
And we're ready to deploy it.

00:30:29.800 --> 00:30:34.800
So we want to create this deployable model object called a Vediver model.

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:40.800
And our inputs into this Vediver model are going to be the model itself that we've created.

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:43.800
And then we're going to give it a name as well.

00:30:43.800 --> 00:30:54.800
And the things that are useful about using this Vediver model object is that it holds on to a lot of information for you.

00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:58.800
Inside this Vediver model, you're going to have things like an input data prototype.

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:04.800
So when you created your model, you, of course, fed it some input data.

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:09.800
And Vediver actually can like slurp that up on its own.

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:12.800
And it knows the data that it should expect as an input.

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:22.800
So if you have five columns and you accidentally put four when you're making a prediction, Vediver will tell you, like, no, that's wrong.

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:29.800
Your data should be five columns or if it has like a wrong date format or something like that.

00:31:29.800 --> 00:31:37.800
This becomes super useful when your model is deployed somewhere that's not on your computer.

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:46.800
It also will say things like what packages are needed to recreate this model and a little bit of metadata about the model itself.

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:59.800
And then with your model board and then your Vediver model created, you can do a function that's just Vediver pin right, your model board, your Vediver model.

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:03.800
And it will actually version your model automatically.

00:32:03.800 --> 00:32:08.800
So this will be wherever you want to place it.

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:15.800
And your board will collect this information, collect this Vediver model.

00:32:15.800 --> 00:32:18.800
And kind of there it is.

00:32:18.800 --> 00:32:20.800
It's meant to be only a few lines of code.

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:29.800
There's a little bit of magic that happens under the surface, but it's supposed to be kind of like a natural extension of what people are already doing.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:35.800
If you wanted to see the metadata that it saves, you can see it has the title.

00:32:35.800 --> 00:32:48.800
It has a description when the model was created, a hash, a little bit more robust versioning system than a bunch of underscore finals, as well as the required packages.

00:32:48.800 --> 00:32:56.800
This used Vediver and scikit-learn.

00:32:56.800 --> 00:33:02.800
There's other things that are beyond just creating these models in Vediver.

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:11.800
MLOps is not just about creating models that are, you know, like in different locations.

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:22.800
It's a lot about documenting and making sure you have good models that are well documented, that are reproducible and can really show what you've learned when you've created this model.

00:33:23.800 --> 00:33:29.800
We believe that, you know, when you've created the model, this is the time where you've spent all of your research.

00:33:29.800 --> 00:33:35.800
And there's no better person to write information about this model than the person who created it.

00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:43.800
So there are a few templates that you can pull up in RStudio.

00:33:43.800 --> 00:33:45.800
One of them is a model card.

00:33:45.800 --> 00:33:58.800
Actually, when you write the model itself, you'll get a little feedback that the model card is a framework for transparent, responsible reporting and to use this Cordo framework as a place to start.

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:12.800
And when you run this code in Python or use the template in RStudio, it gives you something that you can give your pin and it will automatically document what it is able to automatically document.

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:20.800
And then it kind of has fill in the blank type responses for things that a machine can't do.

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:24.800
And that is kind of knowledge that only the model developer would have.

00:34:24.800 --> 00:34:31.800
So you can see, like, it has the model details where you'd have to add your name.

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:34.800
But then it's a place, you know, there's four features.

00:34:34.800 --> 00:34:40.800
This one was created that developer framework will do for you.

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:49.800
It'll also have what your model should expect and a few different plots and analysis on your model.

00:34:49.800 --> 00:34:56.800
At the bottom, there's also some places for you to put ethical considerations and caveats and recommendations.

00:34:56.800 --> 00:35:10.800
Which we believe, you know, even if you don't think that your model has any ethical considerations, that you should at least maybe put none that you know of and to not just delete the section.

00:35:10.800 --> 00:35:22.800
Just if you don't have complete information, it's better to leave something blank to show that you've thought about it than to delete something altogether.

00:35:22.800 --> 00:35:30.800
And so with all of that information, with using pins, you can version your model.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:35.800
And it's kind of the first step in this process of MLOps.

00:35:35.800 --> 00:35:39.800
So you think about saving your model into location that has a robust version.

00:35:39.800 --> 00:35:42.800
It has metadata. It's shareable.

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:50.800
It's not just a file system of you overriding your information.

00:35:50.800 --> 00:35:55.800
So next, we'll go on to deploying your model.

00:35:55.800 --> 00:36:00.800
So you have your model kind of saved in a central location.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:10.800
And at this point, if people want to use it, they have to go to that location, download it, run it in their environment, and kind of hope it works.

00:36:10.800 --> 00:36:14.800
Sometimes things work better on somebody's computer.

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:17.800
Sometimes it's difficult to reproduce exact environments.

00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:24.800
You have to make sure you have all the exact same versions of packages, versions of R.

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:35.800
So we think kind of the ideal scenario here is maybe your model is running somewhere that people can use it without even having to download it.

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:41.800
And that is essentially what deploying your model means.

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:49.800
So deploying your model, you're going to be moving your model here into someplace that is not your computer.

00:36:49.800 --> 00:36:53.800
It's super useful because others can use this model without having to load it.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:59.800
The way that we're going to create this is by using a REST API endpoint.

00:36:59.800 --> 00:37:06.800
An API is kind of an application something process interface.

00:37:06.800 --> 00:37:15.800
Essentially, it is a place where people can ingest your model's information.

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:23.800
The really nice thing about this is that it works with JSON, not necessarily R or Python, to send requests to and from your model.

00:37:23.800 --> 00:37:29.800
So it is pretty language agnostic as long as the input data information is the same.

00:37:29.800 --> 00:37:41.800
So in Python and in R, it is pretty much one-ish lines of code to create a local API endpoint.

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:52.800
In Python, it's putting this Vetiver model V into a Vetiver API and then calling run on it.

00:37:52.800 --> 00:38:04.800
In R, it is also creating a Vetiver API that you're putting a Vetiver model into and running it using Plumber, if you're familiar with Plumber, to make API endpoints.

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:16.800
So this is going to give you a local API running, but, of course, what we had wanted was a model that was not running on our computer.

00:38:16.800 --> 00:38:18.800
We want it to be shared somewhere else.

00:38:18.800 --> 00:38:31.800
So we have a one-liner for Posit Connect, which is like one of Posit's pro products, where if you give it the board and the pin name and the version, it will automatically deploy it as an API endpoint.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:35.800
But there's also ways to do this for Dockerfiles.

00:38:35.800 --> 00:38:45.800
So if you're working for a company that maybe is using a different cloud platform, most of them have a bring-your-own-container ideology.

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:53.800
So as long as you have some sort of Dockerfile, it will kind of automatically slip it up.

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:58.800
It knows how to handle these Dockerfiles and these Docker containers.

00:38:58.800 --> 00:39:07.800
So this prepare Docker call for Python or R will create really three files for you.

00:39:07.800 --> 00:39:15.800
And these three files are what you'll need to deploy your Docker image locally or on another cloud.

00:39:16.800 --> 00:39:27.800
And that's the application file itself, so kind of a plumber.r file, the Dockerfile, to give the system information on how to build the Docker image.

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:32.800
And a requirements.txt in Python or an rnlock file.

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:50.800
So the computer that you're running this new API on will know all the information it needs to, like, download the right packages and make sure it's all of the correct versions as well to ensure reproducibility.

00:39:50.800 --> 00:39:58.800
And with this image, this Docker image, this API endpoint up and running, you're able to just call predict.

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:05.800
So predict with the data that you are running that your model expects.

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:13.800
So that can actually make predictions from this model locally, even if the model itself is not running on your laptop.

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:19.800
So that's what deploying a model looks like.

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:31.800
I think kind of maybe the most famous deployed model right now would be something like chat GPT, where you'll interact with it locally on your laptop.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:36.800
But the model, of course, is running somewhere else with all this information.

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:42.800
But you don't have to be someone who knows how to run chat GPT on your computer.

00:40:42.800 --> 00:40:56.800
All you have to do is interact with it, which I think is really showcasing the beauty of MLOps and what a deployed model should look like and kind of how that should feel.

00:40:56.800 --> 00:40:58.800
I think it's a great thing.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:03.800
So the last piece of this is monitoring a model.

00:41:04.800 --> 00:41:08.800
So when you've created a model, you have your fresh data.

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:09.800
It looks great.

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:13.800
It's performing well.

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:17.800
But that is at the exact point in time when the model is created.

00:41:17.800 --> 00:41:20.800
Oftentimes, data will change over time.

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:28.800
I think of maybe my Spotify or whatever music listening platform I use.

00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:34.800
My music taste is different now than it was five years ago or 10 years ago.

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:37.800
So models have to continually update, train.

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:46.800
If I got the same suggestions for music now as I did earlier, I would probably not be on that platform anymore.

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:48.800
So the same concept applies here.

00:41:48.800 --> 00:41:53.800
Models will degrade over time, will often degrade over time.

00:41:53.800 --> 00:41:55.800
Not all the time.

00:41:55.800 --> 00:42:08.800
But monitoring for MLOps might mean something different if you are a data scientist or if you are a systems admin.

00:42:08.800 --> 00:42:16.800
So what the Vennover framework looks like for MLOps monitoring is the statistical output of the model.

00:42:16.800 --> 00:42:24.800
So it's tracking things like maybe accuracy or R-squared of a model where a systems admin or a DevOps person,

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:33.800
when they think that they're monitoring a model, they might be thinking about like the CPU usage of a model or the run time.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:35.800
So I think if you're collaborating with other teams,

00:42:35.800 --> 00:42:46.800
these are things to keep in mind that you're clear in your expectations of what these kind of loaded terms might mean like monitoring.

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:54.800
In the Vennover framework, there's really three main functions to kind of help people on their monitoring journey.

00:42:54.800 --> 00:43:02.800
It's to compute the metrics where you give it the data, the column that has the date, the time that you want to aggregate over.

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:15.800
So if you want to look at how your model has performed over every one week or one year, the metrics that you're trying to compute.

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:24.800
So things like mean absolute error, R-squared, and then the true value of the model.

00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:28.800
So the model output and the true value.

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:33.800
You can also do things like pin your metrics if you want to continue this information over time,

00:43:33.800 --> 00:43:45.800
if you want to write a small script to check this as you have different information come in, and then to plot the metrics themselves.

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:54.800
There's also another, just like the model card, there's another template in RStudio to build a monitoring dashboard.

00:43:54.800 --> 00:44:05.800
If maybe your company or your team is someone who needs to monitor these models over time and wants a dashboard deployed to help look at that.

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:14.800
So monitoring is extra important because models don't fail loudly.

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:23.800
So if you're thinking about building a Shiny app, when things go wrong in Shiny, you kind of get that, what is it, the skull or like the sad loading screen.

00:44:23.800 --> 00:44:28.800
Things are super broken. Things are not going well.

00:44:28.800 --> 00:44:32.800
And you get this loud error and you know things are not going well.

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:35.800
Models don't work like that. Models will fail silently.

00:44:35.800 --> 00:44:38.800
And they can still run even if there's no error.

00:44:38.800 --> 00:44:42.800
Even if the accuracy is 0%, your model will still give you an output.

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:46.800
This is something we also see with chat GPT, where it'll hallucinate.

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:51.800
You can ask it things. It'll tell you the wrong thing very confidently.

00:44:51.800 --> 00:45:01.800
And that's where monitoring comes in, because if you aren't tracking how your model is performing, you are oblivious if your model is decaying.

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:13.800
So it's really important, whether it's in some sort of large system or something you're doing ad hoc on your own, to do some sort of model monitoring.

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:15.800
And that will complete our cycle.

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:23.800
You have your model versioned as you're creating different experiments, as you're updating your model.

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:25.800
You can deploy your model.

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:27.800
You can monitor your model.

00:45:27.800 --> 00:45:30.800
